> dependant(considering the frequency) on the fact if the system is NTSC or PAL.
> So a gfx card won`t change that. Converting from pal to ntsc time I already
> built in.

Nope, a vertical interrupt depends on what the screenmode of the current screen 
is. And you need to watch out, since not all GFX card/driver/RTG system 
combinations support vertical interrupts.

For example, the Mediator Voodoo drivers only just got that functionality with 
the latest release, and I think UAE suffers from that problem too. I don't know 
about any other GFX cards though.

Without the vertical interrupt, I think they either never occur, or (if you are 
waiting for one), it does a busy-wait loop polling for when the interrupt would 
occur. This is why I posted about a patched REDDebugger - that was the problem 
of it slowing down the system.



What you could do if you are really really wanting to do this in a nice system 
friendly way (which also means a lot of work and heartache when you find out 
Blitz sucks for doing this :) is to set up a separate task for controlling the 
timing and serial port. Then use timer.device for timing the interrupts and 
serial.device for sending the stuff. Don't ask for an example from me, I don't 
have any :)

