> Miasto.s
> Kod.s
> Email.s
> Tel.s
> End NEWTYPE

This is your problem.   You do not raed files with a newtype in this
manner.   Simply do a Get filenumber, recordnumber and that will fill
in all the fields for you.   If you look at the file with a hex
editor, you will find that the fields are stored in reverse order for
each record.   FIELDS a.l,b.l,c.l will store c first, then b then a.  
Also strings have a 6-byte overhead (4 byte length at the front and 2
byte pad at the back).

All you need to do to create a new record is to fill the fields and
Put filenumber, recordnumber  where recordnumber is not greater than
the current number of records.    Remeber that the first record is
record zero.

You CAN use NewTypes, but that involves using fileseek and ReadMem \
WriteMem commands.   Also strings have to be inserted with
poke,s and extracted with peek.s

If you need any more help, let me know.  I've done a lot of stuff with
random access files.

